BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:S8XJCYwB_CTMHUVekinzY
SUMMARY:Artist's Way Classes Winter 2026 are Now Open for Registration
DTSTAMP:20260330T060553Z
DTSTART:20260409T013000Z
DESCRIPTION:The Artist's Way Classes for Winter 2026 via Zoom or In-Person 
	are Now Open for Registration The Artist's Way by Julia Cameron is an inte
	rnational bestseller on the subject of creativity. Whether you see yoursel
	f as an artist or not\, this book and class can be an incredibly useful re
	source to tap into your creative side which can benefit many parts of your
	 life. Led by Creativity Instructor\, Kate Gavigan\, the 2 hour a week 12 
	week long class will take students through the 12 chapters with an emphasi
	s on the accompanying chapter exercises and additional creativity exercise
	s and strategies \\(i.e. meditation tools\\). This material can work with 
	anyone\, no matter how dormant or energized their creative life may be.  S
	tudents report that as a result of going through our Artist's Way class th
	ey more fully and genuinely know themselves\, they discover or re-discover
	 their gifts and talents and have more fun and joy in their lives.\n\nTo q
	uote Julia\, "In order to retrieve your creativity\, you need to find it."
	 The basic tools and the additional creativity exercises that we incorpora
	te into the 12 week course can help you do just that. No prerequisites req
	uired for this class.  Students also meet with the instructor for a one on
	 one chat on Zoom for 30 minutes prior to the first class and before the l
	ast class.\n\nSection I: January 19 – April 6 – via Zoom Monday Mornings\,
	 10:00 am – noon $395 \\(12 weeks\\) OR\n\nSection II:  January 19 – April
	 6 - via Zoom Monday Evenings\, 6:30 – 8:30 pm \\(Pacific Standard time\\)
	 $395 \\(12 weeks\\) OR\n\nSection III:  – January 21 – April 8 via Zoom W
	ednesdays\, 3:00 – 5:00 pm \\(Pacific Standard time\\) $395 \\(12 weeks\\)
	 OR\n\nSection IV: January 21 – April 8 via In-PERSON Wednesdays\, 6:30 – 
	8:30 pm \\(Pacific Standard time\\) $395 \\(12 weeks\\) This In-Person Cla
	ss held in West Seattle at the Fauntleroy Schoolhouse\, 9131 California Av
	e. SW\, Seattle\, WA Instructor for all sections: Kate Gavigan Note: Stude
	nts will use the book The Artist’s Way by Julia Cameron. Students are resp
	onsible for purchasing their own copy of The Artist’s Way by Julia Cameron
	.\n\nTo Register or for more information: https://seattleartistswaycenter.
	com/class-offerings\n\nFor testimonials from past students: https://seattl
	eartistswaycenter.com/class-testimonials\n\nKate Gavigan is passionate abo
	ut The Artist's Way after offering classes since 2009 and seeing the posit
	ive changes in her students' lives and having personally experienced the b
	enefits of the materials. Kate worked in social services as a trainer for 
	over 10 years when she found herself drawn to the material in The Artist's
	 Way\, which helped her uncover a passion for theatre and the arts. She cr
	edits her mid-life career change \\(now working at her dream jobs as an Ar
	tist's Way Instructor and Speaker since 2009\, a Creativity Coach\, a Home
	 Organizer and pursuing her interest in Acting and Music\\) to having gone
	 through The Artist's Way.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/detail
	s/artist-s-way-classes-winter-2026-are-now-open-for-registration/17381451/
	2026-04-08T00
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/artist-s-way-classes-wint
	er-2026-are-now-open-for-registration/17381451/2026-04-08T00
LOCATION:The Fauntleroy Schoolhouse\, 9131 California Avenue SW\, Seattle\,
	 WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:tYS0sNLSOGy173664Mwwq
SUMMARY:Beyond Mysticism: The Modern Northwest
DTSTAMP:20260330T060553Z
DTSTART:20260409T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:image: Drift No. 2\, 1936\, Malcolm M. Roberts\, American\, 191
	3-1990\, tempera on board\, 25 1/2 x 20 5/8 in.\, Seattle Art Museum\, Eug
	ene Fuller Memorial Collection\, 37.103\, © Malcolm M. Roberts\, photo: Sc
	ott Leen.\n\nInspired by the region’s natural beauty and rapidly changing 
	city\, this exhibition showcases artists who told the raw story of Seattle
	 in the 20th century. By sharing the Pacific Northwest’s perspective throu
	gh trending art styles—including Social Realism\, Surrealism\, and Abstrac
	t Expressionism—these artists offered a unique take on Modernist art and c
	hallenged the “mystic” label ascribed to their works.\n\nSpearheading the 
	movement were local icons Mark Tobey\, Kenneth Callahan\, Guy Anderson\, a
	nd Morris Graves—but the range and breadth of Pacific Northwest art goes b
	eyond the “Big Four” of the Northwest School. Featuring more than 150 piec
	es\, this exhibition showcases works that investigate the complexities of 
	daily life in the region. Whether applying an ecocritical lens or producin
	g dreamy and uncanny visuals\, these artists expressed the duality of the 
	natural world and city life to warn of the environmental and social impact
	s of industrialization.\n\nFrom Malcolm Roberts to Kenjiro Nomura\, learn 
	how Northwest artists applied their regional perspective to broader artist
	ic developments to create a new form of American Modernism.\n\nThe exhibit
	ion is accompanied by a fully illustrated catalogue authored by Theresa Pa
	panikolas\, SAM’s Ann M. Barwick Curator of American Art.\n\nhttps://seato
	day.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-modern-northwest/183
	08126/2026-04-09T00
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-mode
	rn-northwest/18308126/2026-04-09T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:Kq5Yt85IyqPg2YYJJwJZS
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260330T060553Z
DTSTART:20260409T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-09T00
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-09T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:WDFW1Hw7aqoJ-zi6c9Ym7
SUMMARY:Samantha Yun Wall: What We Leave Behind
DTSTAMP:20260330T060553Z
DTSTART:20260409T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Samantha Yun Wall’s new paintings use overlapping silhouettes o
	f female figures as portals to unknown spaces and different temporal realm
	s. Impetus for the new body of work is a Korean folk tale in which the Pas
	que flower is symbolic of a grandmother who passed away without the loving
	 care of her grandchildren. It is a story of melancholy\, loss\, and remem
	brance. The delicate hair on the flower’s stem differentiates it\, and the
	 artist gives the plant a surreal aspect in some of her paintings\, replac
	ing the flower’s center with a watchful eye.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we-leave-behind/18026187/2026-0
	4-09T00
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we
	-leave-behind/18026187/2026-04-09T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:1kThdNeLt0DiEUZ8aAVNb
SUMMARY:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light
DTSTAMP:20260330T060553Z
DTSTART:20260409T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light invites you to become par
	t of the art. Agha\, a Pakistani American artist\, animates spaces with he
	r large-scale sculptural installations. Suspended from the ceiling\, Agha’
	s steel cubes are laser-cut with intricate designs that project geometric 
	shadows onto the visitor. She draws on both the light and dark of her own 
	life\, using South Asian art practices to convey the gender discrimination
	 she faced growing up as a young girl in Pakistan. An in-depth exploration
	 of Islamic architecture\, art\, and identity\, this is the first solo exh
	ibition of a Pakistani American artist in SAM’s 90-year history. Agha is c
	arving a name out for herself in the art world—visit the Seattle Asian Art
	 Museum for an immersive and illuminating experience.\n\nhttps://seatoday.
	6amcity.com/events/#/details/anila-quayyum-agha-geometry-of-light/16795597
	/2026-04-09T00
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/anila-quayyum-agha-geomet
	ry-of-light/16795597/2026-04-09T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:aPHzAaoUbtJ46Q3Z9Y2V3
SUMMARY:Boren Banner Series: Camille Trautman
DTSTAMP:20260330T060553Z
DTSTART:20260409T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Every photograph is a reminder that the act of framing is never
	 neutral. In Camille Trautman’s first solo museum exhibition in their home
	town\, the Seattle-born Duwamish artist uses photography and video to chal
	lenge colonial narratives and counter Indigenous erasure. The exhibition p
	resents selections from their ongoing series The North American LCD—spectr
	al self-portraits staged in varied natural landscapes. Rooted in Trautman’
	s process of coming out as transgender\, the images show the artist’s body
	 partially obscured by large LCD screens. The series examines how both lan
	dscape photography and digital media can shape or distort cultural identit
	y\, often by promoting or denying visibility.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.
	com/events/#/details/boren-banner-series-camille-trautman/16813305/2026-04
	-09T00
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/boren-banner-series-camil
	le-trautman/16813305/2026-04-09T00
LOCATION:Frye Art Museum\, 704 Terry Ave\, Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT6H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:jzPg6OlDQx81Lg2bj9pa7
SUMMARY:Scott Gibson - Visual Symphony II
DTSTAMP:20260330T060553Z
DTSTART:20260409T190000Z
DESCRIPTION:In March\, Visual Symphony II Scott Gibson invites viewers into
	 a world where music and art collide. Each work is an exploration of the v
	ivid\, sensory experience of sound translating into vibrant\, emotional vi
	suals. As an artist with synesthesia each work expresses Scott’s personal 
	perception of what music looks like. Scott uses resin techniques that he h
	as pioneered and pushes the boundaries of this medium.\n\nhttps://seatoday
	.6amcity.com/events/#/details/scott-gibson-visual-symphony-ii/18280602/202
	6-04-09T00
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/scott-gibson-visual-symph
	ony-ii/18280602/2026-04-09T00
LOCATION:Gray Sky Gallery\, 320 First Ave. S.\, Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT4H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:MzTcXFU9gf1LdoMzCL_yL
SUMMARY:Contemporary Dance for Every Body
DTSTAMP:20260330T060553Z
DTSTART:20260409T230000Z
DESCRIPTION:Class Overview\n\nWould you like to cultivate body awareness th
	rough movement? Explore a grounded and natural approach to moving your bod
	y\, led by a contemporary dance instructor.\n\nThrough floorwork\, movemen
	t sequences\, and phrasing\, this class cultivates body awareness. Explore
	 efficiency in movement transitions. Develop a deeper understanding of how
	 your body moves naturally in relation to the floor\, emphasizing organic 
	flow\, continuity\, spirality\, softness\, core engagement\, and the intel
	ligent use of gravity.\n\nOpen your mind and body through guided movement!
	 Explore points of support\, releasing tension\, and engaging the core to 
	facilitate flow and prevent injury. Movement principles will draw from con
	temporary dance and somatic practices\, encouraging dancers to move with c
	larity\, sensitivity\, and presence.\n\nThis class is for dancers\, actors
	\, physical theater artists\, yoga/movement practitioners\, and anyone int
	erested in exploring movement in their bodies -- no experience necessary. 
	Designed to be inclusive\, this class offers both accessibility and challe
	nge to movers at various levels and all backgrounds. \n\nLearning Objectiv
	es\n\nUnderstand and embody key principles of movement floorwork\, includi
	ng gravity\, spirality\, and core initiation.\n\nImprove movement continui
	ty and flow between levels \\(floor to standing and vice versa\\).\n\nExpl
	ore softness and efficiency through core engagement.\n\nIdentify and use a
	natomical points of support for safe and fluid movement.\n\nDevelop new da
	nce tools\n\nFeel more connected with the possibilities of your body in a 
	conscious way to live a more present\, healthy\, and aware life.\n\nWho Mi
	ght Enjoy This Class? \n\nAdult learners of all backgrounds \\(18\\+\\)\, 
	including dancers\, actors\, physical theater artists\, yoga/movement prac
	titioners\n\nAnyone interested in embodied movement practices.\n\nSome pri
	or movement or dance experience is helpful but not required. The class wil
	l be structured to accommodate varying levels of experience and physical a
	bility.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/contemporary-danc
	e-for-every-body/18345436/2026-04-09T00
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/contemporary-dance-for-ev
	ery-body/18345436/2026-04-09T00
LOCATION:Seattle Central College Continuing Education\, 1701 Broadway\, Sea
	ttle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H30M
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:Z6yU8Jk3U7CkOlUIDmsmF
SUMMARY:Drop-in Drawing
DTSTAMP:20260330T060553Z
DTSTART:20260410T000000Z
DESCRIPTION:Deepen your connection to art through the meditative act of dra
	wing! Every second Thursday\, the Frye galleries become a welcoming space 
	to drop-in\, slow down\, and draw inspiration from the works on view. Frye
	 teaching artists are present to support your drawing\, encourage close lo
	oking\, and help create a relaxed\, self-guided experience. Come solo or w
	ith a friend\; stay for fifteen minutes or settle in for the full session—
	the choice is yours. All skill levels are welcome\, and youth may particip
	ate with an accompanying adult. Materials are provided. --- https://fryemu
	seum.org/calendar/event/drop-in-drawing-2026\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/drop-in-drawing/17134817/2026-04-09T00
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/drop-in-drawing/17134817/
	2026-04-09T00
LOCATION:Frye Art Museum\, 704 Terry Ave\, Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H30M
END:VEVENT
